'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|qid=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Anpachi District|Q1204320|qid=Q1204320|1=Anpachi District, Gifu}}{{ill|lt=Wanouchi Town|Q1204291|qid=Q1204291|1=Wanouchi, Gifu}}.

It is the Kamo Shrine of Anpachi District in {{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|qid=Q864156|1=Mino Province}} listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and is considered one of the {{ill|lt=Kamo Shrines|Q11398885|qid=Q11398885|1=Kamo Shrine (disambiguation)}} (Kamo Shrine / Kamo Shrine) found throughout Japan.

=== History and Overview ===
The date of founding is unknown. It is said that {{ill|lt=Kamone no Ōkimi|Q119380336|qid=Q119380336|1=Kami Ōne}} (son of {{ill|lt=Hikozawano Ōkimi|Q11487910|qid=Q11487910|1=Hikoimasu no Ōkimi}}; ancestor of the {{ill|lt=Motosu no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q11520234|qid=Q11520234|1=Motosu no Kuni no Miyatsuko}} and {{ill|lt=Mino no Saki no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q11358204|qid=Q11358204|1=Mino no Saki no Kuni no Miyatsuko}}) or his descendants enshrined their ancestral deity, Kambe Wakareikazuchi no Mikoto, when they cultivated this land.<ref name="岐阜県神社庁">[https://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=64&shrname=%E2%98%85%E5%8A%A0%E6%AF%9B%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E2%98%85 Kamo Shrine (Gifu Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines)]</ref>.

The original name at the time of founding was Kamo Shrine (in the Mino Province Jinmyōchō it appears as “Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade Kamo Myōjin”<ref name="岐阜県神社庁"/><ref name="加毛神社"/>), but from around the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|qid=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}} it became a shrine enshrining {{ill|lt=Sarutahiko|Q3090037|qid=Q3090037|lt=Shirahige Daimyōjin|1=Sarutahiko Ōkami}} and was renamed Shirahige Shrine. For this reason, some documents still list the enshrined deity as “Shirahige Daimyōjin.”

In {{ill|lt=1869|Q7720|qid=Q7720|1=1869}} (Meiji 2), it was renamed Kamo Shrine, and in {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}} (Meiji 6) it was designated a {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.<ref name="岐阜県神社庁"/><ref name="かんこう輪之内">{{Cite web|language=Japanese|url=https://kanko.washoko.or.jp/detail.php?id=24|title=Kamo Shrine|publisher=Wanouchi Town Chamber of Commerce and Industry|accessdate=2025-11-14}}</ref>

In {{ill|lt=1976|Q2480|qid=Q2480|1=1976}} (Shōwa 51), it was designated a {{ill|lt=Kinpeisha|Q119929592|qid=Q119929592|lt=Ginpeisha|1=Kinpei-sha}} by the Gifu Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines.<ref name="加毛神社">[https://kamo-shrine.jp/ Kamo Shrine]</ref>

=== Enshrined Deity ===
* {{ill|lt=Kamo Wakeikazuchi no Mikoto|Q11634943|qid=Q11634943|lt=Kambe Wakareikazuchi no Mikoto|1=Kamo-wake-ikazuchi-no-Kami}}
: There is also a theory that the deity is {{ill|lt=Sarutahiko|Q3090037|qid=Q3090037|lt=Shirahige Daimyōjin|1=Sarutahiko Ōkami}}.

=== Major Festivals ===
* Ganshi-sai – January 3
* {{ill|lt=Sagichō|Q9332740|qid=Q9332740|1=Sagichō Fire Festival}} – Second Sunday of January
* Kayutsuke Shinji – The day after Sagichō
* Kinen-sai – First Sunday of March
* Annual Festival – September 30
* Parishioners’ Thanksgiving Festival (Kamo Shrine Festival) – Second Sunday of October

=== Location ===
* 13017 Shimōgure Higashi-ise, Wanouchi Town, Anpachi District, Gifu Prefecture
: On the right bank of the {{ill|lt=Ōgure River|Q11436448|qid=Q11436448|1=Ōgure River}} (a tributary of the {{ill|lt=Nagara River|Q1194094|qid=Q1194094|1=Nagara River}}), in the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Fukutsuka Wajū|1=UNKNOWN}}

